inning the early transnational recording industry, highlighting the multiple gestures and forms of labour entombed within the production of the 78rpm disc. Roy explores shellac as a concrete substance, as well as the malleable stuff of which stories, histories and modern imaginings were made – and unmade.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aShellac. 0aSound recording industryxHistory. 4aArt and Material Culture. 4aCultural Studies. 4aFilm, Media, and Communication. 4aInterdisciplinary Studies. 4aMedia Studies. 4aScience and Technology. 7aSCIENCE / Scientific Instruments.2bisacsh  aPhonography, media, materiality, waste, colonialism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311102374840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048553143?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048553143423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789048553143/original  a978-3-11-102374-8  Amsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles